* is there a pattern that all nsswitch client subjects want to read machine runtime files?

* implement system_map_t for /boot/System.map.* files?

* vlock

* probably should rethink socket activation completely (also specify the sockets)

    examples

    network socket activation:

    (call systemd_tcp_socket_activated_subject_type (sshd_t))
    (call systemd_tcp_socket_activated_object_type (ssh_port_t))

    translates to:

    (allow systemd_t sshd_t create_tcp_stream_socket_perms)
    (allow systemd_t ssh_port_t (tcp_socket (name_bind)))

    netlink socket activation:

    (call systemd_netlink_socket_activated_subject_type (udevd_t netlink_kobject_uevent_socket))

    translates to:

    (allow systemd_t udevd_t (netlink_kobject_uevent_socket (...))) # where ... is "create_netlink_socket_perms"

    file socket activation:

    (call systemd_unix_stream_socket_activated_subject_type (dbusd_t))
    (call systemd_socket_activated_object_type (dbusd_lib_t))

    translates to:

    (allow systemd_t systemd_socket_activated_file_object_type create_dir_perms)

    (allow systemd_t dbusd_t create_unix_stream_stream_socket_perms)
    (call create_sock_files_pattern (systemd_t dbusd_lib_t dbusd_lib_t))

    note that currently udevd netlink_kobject_uevent_socket, networkd netlink_route_socket, and journald netlink_audit_socket activation is
    implemented independent of my current socket activation solution, and that i should merge that eventually.

